    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-04-25T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-04-25T11:00:00-05:00" n="21"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.65/549: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-04-25T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 25, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 25—2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>650. The British Ambassador told me today that Hore-Belisha<note n="70"
                        xml:id="d21fn70">Leslie Hore-Belisha, British Secretary of State for
                        War.</note> who left here at noon for London was enthusiastic over his Rome
                    visit. He said that Mussolini had been most cordial and that the atmosphere had
                    completely changed as regards Italian feeling towards England. He said that he
                    had found genuine apprehension in Rome regarding future relations with Germany.
                    He had gathered the impression that the Franco-Italian discussions were going
                    satisfactorily and that after Ciano’s return from Albania they would be
                    concluded without difficulty.</p>
                <p>A friend who saw Hore-Belisha off at the air port was told by him that in his
                    talk with Daladier last night he had urged that the French be as reasonable as
                    the British in forthcoming negotiations and that he had in mind particularly
                    negotiations with Germany.</p>
                <p>Copies to London, Berlin and Rome.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
